            <pb facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">The Book of Job.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;The book of<lb break="yes"/>Job is generally regarded as the most<lb
                        break="yes"/>perfect specimen of the poetry of the<lb break="yes"/>Hebrews.
                    It is alike picturesque in<lb break="yes"/>the delineation of individual
                    phenome-<lb break="no"/>na and artistical skillful in the <choice><sic>didacit-<lb
                        break="no"/>ic</sic><corr type="editorial">didact-<lb
                            break="no"/>ic</corr></choice> arrangement of the whole work.&#x2014;<lb break="yes"/>In all
                    the modern languages into which<lb break="yes"/>the book of Job has been
                    translated, its<lb break="yes"/>images, drawn from the natural scene-<lb
                        break="no"/>ry of the East, leave a deep impression<lb break="yes"/>on the
                    mind. &#x201C;The Lord walketh on<lb break="yes"/>the heights of the waters, on
                    the ridges<lb break="yes"/>of the wave towering high beneath the<lb break="yes"
                    />force of the wind.&#x201D; &#x201C;The morning<lb break="yes"/>red has covered
                    the margin of the<lb break="yes"/>earth, and variously forming the cov-<lb
                        break="no"/>ering of the clouds, as the son of man<lb break="yes"/>holds the
                    yielding clay. The habits<lb break="yes"/>of animals are described, as, for
                        in-<lb break="no"/>stance, those of the wild ass, the horse,<lb break="yes"
                    />the buffalo, the rhinocerous, and the<lb break="yes"/>crocodile, the eagle,
                    and the ostrich.<lb break="yes"/>We see &#x201C;the pure ether spread, during<lb
                        break="yes"/>the heat of the south wind, as a melted<lb break="yes"/>mirror,
                    over the parched desert.&#x201D; The<lb break="yes"/>poetic literature of the
                    Hebrews is not<lb break="yes"/><choice><sic>defiecient</sic><corr type="editorial">deficient</corr></choice> in variety of form; for while<lb
                        break="yes"/>the Hebrew poetry breathes a warlike<lb break="yes"
                    />enthusiasm, from Joshua to Samuel,<lb break="yes"/>the little book of the
                    gleaner Ruth<lb break="yes"/>presents us with a charming and ex-<lb break="no"
                    />quisite picture of nature. Goethe, at<lb break="yes"/>the period of his
                    enthusiasm for the<lb break="yes"/>East, spoke of it as the loveliest speci-<lb
                        break="no"/>men of epic and idly poetry which we<lb break="yes"
                        />possess.&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i">Humboldts Cosmos, vol ii, p,</hi>
                    <lb break="yes"/>60.</p>
            </div>
